After hearing that movers had been comtracted for this affair, I was under the impression that if any assistance was to be required of me, my efforts might necessitate a couple of hours of work. Then I learned two days ago that I had even been requested to lend aid at all!

No one initially knew how taxing any of this would be on all of us thanks to rather surprisingly poor preparation for the move itself from my uncle. Everything was essentially business as usual this past week for the company with most tools coming out of production *today!*

Filing cabinets (filled with files, of course), desks, chairs, computers, printers, shredder, customer area furniture and 5 gallon containers of water were all loaded and moved by us, as well, with additional aid from my mother, aunt, and another cousin.

The 5 of us family members worked from 8AM-2:30PM moving things up to half a ton in weight with simple dollies and furniture dollies. All of us were completely bereft of energy afterward. In addition to this, the office and customer area also had to make the move, as well.

For a business with 4 employees, there was nothing small about this relocation effort. My brother, two cousins, uncle, and myself made up 5 men from our family to make the move happen. 4 movers were hired for 2 hours for all *9* of us to move tooling, storage, and machinery.

Thanks to a surprising alignment of vacation plans and piano placement exams among my students, I was free from teaching today. My aunt and uncle chose this weekend to move their small business to a new location after 18 years.

Finally, I think all of these services could be more aggressive on pricing like @medicitv and their mainstream counterparts are at various times of year. I think all of these are better options than for the Met to continue offering free nightly streams.

Yes, I know there is a difference here because Disney has ownership stakes in all three of the combined properties with that respective bundle deal, but as opera streaming exists now, I have to choose carefully which companies I want to access since my capital is not limitless.

For example, imagine if you could pay something like $12.99/month to have access to the Met, the ROH, Opera de Paris, La Scala, and the Wiener Staatsoper's digital catalogs like Disney, Hulu and ESPN offer for their services. That seems like a forward-thinking initiative.

What could improve with the Met's streaming service? I would love to see them partner with other opera companies to provide access to an even larger catalog of performances *without* substantially raising the rate for their streaming service. I also think the cost is a bit high.

The @MetOpera has a subscription based streaming service. If an evening of streamed opera is preferred entertainment for anyone, they can easily and semi-affordably subscribe. Should Netflix offer free, nightly streams? Furthermore, opera is *very* accessible online today. https://t.co/ozvaWkrZKN
